    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "gotcha. so it's basically all about that interface layer. i was reading something about how the texture of the rebar—like those ribs on the surface—helps with that bond. does that physical texture actually change how the load is distributed internally, or is it just more about preventing slipping?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The ribs on the rebar, often called deformations or lugs, are absolutely critical, and they do much more than just prevent slipping—though that's a huge part of it! These ribs dramatically increase the **surface area** between the concrete and the steel.\n\nThis increased surface area allows for a much more robust mechanical interlock. Instead of just relying on the chemical adhesion (which can be compromised by moisture or chemicals), the ribs physically key themselves into the concrete as it cures. This mechanical keying ensures that when the concrete tries to pull away, it has to break those physical anchors, which requires significantly more force than just overcoming a smooth surface. It's a brilliant, brute-force engineering solution!",
      "source": "target",
